<p>

<indent level="1">

<it>In this <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../225/164225.xml">
Japanese name</link>, the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../814/10814.xml">
family name</link> is </it>Hisao<it>.</it>
</indent>
<b>Juran Hisao (久生十蘭, Hisao Jūran)</b>; (<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../008/1008.xml">
6 April</link> <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../652/34652.xml">
1902</link> - <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../542/22542.xml">
6 October</link> <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../606/34606.xml">
1957</link>) was the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../043/46043.xml">
pen-name</link> of a Japanese author of popular fiction in <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../240/261240.xml">
Showa period</link> <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../573/15573.xml">
Japan</link>. His real name was <b>Masao Abe</b> (阿部 正雄, Abe Masao).</p>

<sec>
<st>
Early life</st>
<p>

Jūran was a native of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../547/204547.xml">
Hakodate</link> on the northern Japanese island of <link>
Hokkaidō</link>. While working for the Hakodate branch of the <newspaper wordnetid="106267145" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../128/318128.xml">
Mainichi Shimbun</link></newspaper>
 newspaper, he wrote poetry and drama his spare time. </p>
<p>

In 1926, he moved to <region wordnetid="108630985" confidence="0.8">
<administrative_district wordnetid="108491826" confidence="0.8">
